SIMPLE: wisdom
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wisdom
<hw>Wis"dom</hw> <pr>(-d⟦ucr⟧m)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>w⟦imac⟧sd⟦omac⟧m</ets>. See <er>Wise</er>, <pos>a.</pos>, and
<er>-dom</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The quality of being wise; knowledge, and the
capacity to make due use of it; knowledge of the best ends and the best
means; discernment and judgment; discretion; sagacity; skill;
dexterity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We speak also not in wise words of man's <qex>wisdom</qex>, but in
the doctrine of the spirit.</q> <rj><qau>Wyclif (1 Cor. ii.
13).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q> Behold, the fear of the Lord, that is <qex>wisdom</qex>; and to
depart from evil is understanding.</q> <rj><qau>Job xxviii.
28.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>It</qex> is hoped that our rulers will act with dignity and
<qex>wisdom</qex> that they will yield everything to reason, and refuse
everything to force.</q> <rj><qau>Ames.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Common sense in an uncommon degree is what the world calls
<qex>wisdom</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The results of wise judgments; scientific or
practical truth; acquired knowledge; erudition.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Moses was learned in all the <qex>wisdom</qex> of the Egyptians,
and was mighty in words and in deeds.</q> <rj><qau>Acts vii.
22.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Prudence; knowledge.</syn> <usage>
<er>Wisdom</er>, <er>Prudence</er>, <er>Knowledge</er>.
<xex>Wisdom</xex> has been defined to be ⟦ldquo⟧the use of the best
means for attaining the best ends.⟦rdquo⟧ ⟦ldquo⟧We conceive,⟦rdquo⟧
says Whewell, ⟦ldquo⟧ <xex>prudence</xex> as the virtue by which we
select right means for given ends, while <xex>wisdom</xex> implies the
selection of right ends as well as of right means.⟦rdquo⟧ Hence,
<xex>wisdom</xex> implies the union of high mental and moral excellence.
<xex>Prudence</xex> (that is, <xex>providence</xex>, or forecast) is of
a more negative character; it rather consists in avoiding danger than in
taking decisive measures for the accomplishment of an object. Sir Robert
Walpole was in many respects a <xex>prudent</xex> statesman, but he was
far from being a <xex>wise</xex> one. Burke has said that
<xex>prudence</xex>, when carried too far, degenerates into a
⟦ldquo⟧reptile virtue,⟦rdquo⟧ which is the more dangerous for its
plausible appearance. <xex>Knowledge</xex>, a more comprehensive term,
signifies the simple apprehension of facts or relations. ⟦ldquo⟧In
strictness of language,⟦rdquo⟧ says Paley, ⟦ldquo⟧ there is a difference
between <xex>knowledge</xex> and <xex>wisdom</xex>; <xex>wisdom</xex>
always supposing action, and action directed by it.⟦rdquo⟧</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Knowledge</qex> and <qex>wisdom</qex>, far from being
one,⟦br⟧
Have ofttimes no connection. <qex>Knowledge</qex> dwells⟦br⟧
In heads replete with thoughts of other men;⟦br⟧
<qex>Wisdom</qex>, in minds attentive to their own.⟦br⟧
<qex>Knowledge</qex>, a rude, unprofitable mass,⟦br⟧
The mere materials with which <qex>wisdom</qex> builds,⟦br⟧
Till smoothed, and squared, and fitted to its place,⟦br⟧
Does but encumber whom it seems to enrich.⟦br⟧
<qex>Knowledge</qex> is proud that he has learned so much;⟦br⟧
<qex>Wisdom</qex> is humble that he knows no more.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Wisdom tooth</b></col>, <cd>the last, or back, tooth of
the full set on each half of each jaw in man; -- familiarly so called,
because appearing comparatively late, after the person may be supposed
to have arrived at the age of wisdom. See the Note under <er>Tooth</er>,
1.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wisdom literature</ent>⟦br⟧
